<p><b>Giuseppe Garibaldi</b> (July 4, 1807 – June 2, 1882) was an <a href="/wiki/Italians" title="Italians">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Military" title="Military">military</a> and <a href="/wiki/Political" title="Political" class="mw-redirect">political</a> figure. In his twenties, he joined the <a href="/wiki/Carbonari" title="Carbonari">Carbonari</a> Italian patriot revolutionaries, and had to flee Italy after a failed insurrection. He then contributed to the independence of <a href="/wiki/Uruguay" title="Uruguay">Uruguay</a>, leading the Italian Legion in the <a href="/wiki/Uruguayan_Civil_War" title="Uruguayan Civil War">Uruguayan Civil War</a>, and afterwards returned to Italy as a commander in the conflicts of the <a href="/wiki/Unification_of_Italy" title="Unification of Italy" class="mw-redirect">Risorgimento</a>.</p>
<p>He has been dubbed the "Hero of the Two Worlds" in tribute to his military expeditions in both South America and Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> He is considered an Italian national hero.</p>
